  "text": "CORRESPONDENCE 13 May 2025 By Jing Wu1, Muhammad Sheraz2 \u0026 … Quande Qin3 Avik Sinha Xi’an Jiaotong-Liverpool University, Suzhou, China. Jing Wu Xi’an Jiaotong-Liverpool University, Suzhou, China. Muhammad Sheraz Shenzhen University, Shenzhen, China. Quande Qin Shenzhen University, Shenzhen, China. Government subsidies, tax exemptions and technological innovation have contributed to China becoming a global leader in electric vehicle (EV) manufacturing. In 2023, the country accounted for nearly 60% of new EV registrations globally. In September 2024, 1.29 million EVs were sold in China, a 42% increase from 2023. But with consumers preferring new EVs over second-hand ones, discarded EVs are intensifying battery-recycling needs. Access options Access Nature and 54 other Nature Portfolio journals Get Nature+, our best-value online-access subscription $29.99 / 30 days cancel any time Subscribe to this journal Receive 51 print issues and online access $199.00 per year only $3.90 per issue Rent or buy this article Prices vary by article type from$1.95 to$39.95 Prices may be subject to local taxes which are calculated during checkout Additional access options: Log in Learn about institutional subscriptions Read our FAQs Contact customer support Nature 641, 594 (2025) doi: https://doi.org/10.1038/d41586-025-01508-y Competing Interests The authors declare no competing interests. Related Articles Drive to electrify Electric cars could save billions in health-care costs See more letters to the editor Subjects Latest on:",
